{
  "answer": "**In the *Nāradasmṛti*, the rule addressing a seller who misrepresents goods appears in the section on \"Non-delivery of a Sold Article\" (one of the 18 topics of litigation).**\n\nSpecifically: \"He who, having shown a faultless article, delivers a faulty one, shall be made to pay double the price, and a fine of the same amount.\"[^1]\n\nThis covers the scenario where a seller displays non-defective property but substitutes defective goods upon delivery, which constitutes misrepresentation. The buyer may seek double the price as compensation, plus an equal fine imposed by the king.\n\nThe text distinguishes this from buyer rescission rights (e.g., returning goods after self-examination for defects under Topic 9), unauthorized sales by non-owners (Topic 7), or general sales rules.[^2]\n\n[^1]: *Nāradasmṛti*, Chapter 1, [p-5046aa](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-5046aa).\n[^2]: *Nāradasmṛti*, Chapter 1, [p-cea9fd](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-cea9fd) (Topic 7); [p-ec4b23](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-ec4b23) (Topic 9).",
